post_text:
Exciting news! The USDA has allowed sponsors to participate in a fall "summer feeding". What does that mean for our Holland kids? Well, every child 1-18 years of age eat for free! That's right FREE.
This will only be for the fall and will end Dec 31 or until the funds are no longer available. Any child in the area and our HISD virtual learners may pick up breakfast and lunch in the cafeteria foyer between the hours of 11:30 am to noon. Parents of non-student children who wish to pick up lunches without the child present must bring identification for the child (ex. birth certificate). If you have any questions please feel free to message me, email at cknaus@hollandisd.org, or call 254-657-2265.

https://squaremeals.org/News/tabid/945/Article/2977/USDA-Extends-Free-Meals-for-Kids-Through-December-31-2020.aspx

First Day of School Reminders for Holland Middle School

If you are a 6th grader or a 7th/8th grade non athlete, report to the cafeteria. Before 7:30 sit in an available desk under the awning. After 7:30 enter the cafeteria. You may eat breakfast in the cafeteria. We will be present to help you with supplies. You will receive schedules in the cafeteria.

If you are a 7th/8th grade athlete, report to the Holland Gym (main gym) with any supplies. Coaches will help you with supplies. You will receive schedules in the gym. Your Grab and Go breakfast is available between 1st and 2nd period, as usual.

You must wear a mask/face covering.

Remember to bring a water bottle.

Microwaves are not available for use at lunch.

We can‚Äôt wait to see you!!

post_text:
ATTENTION HOLLAND ISD:

Due to inclement weather the Varsity football game at Bosqueville (9/4/20) has been changed. The Hornets are not playing IN Bosqueville, we are now playing the game AT HOME! Same team, different location. 7:30 p.m.
The game will be broadcast via Facebook live on the HISD Facebook page.

Parking Info: Due to the weather, parking for the home fans is not available at this time. Please use the main parking area by the gym. Home fans will ENTER THROUGH THE GYM, visitors will enter through the main entrance.

Concessions will be open but there will be a limited supply. (Chips, pickles, candy and drinks will be offered - no hot food.) Sausage wraps will be sold by the Holland Cornfest crew for $4.00

Ticket Information: Game tickets will be on sale at 1:00 on Friday at the Holland ISD Administration office. Tickets are $5.00. Season tickets which were already purchased for the Bosqueville away game, will be accepted at home.

Please remember: FACE-COVERINGS REQUIRED

Please share the post so everyone knows. Thank you. Go Hornets!!

post_text: We are so thankful for our school and community. Thank you Melany, you said it perfectly! Go Hornets!
shared_text:
Melany Parmer Cearley is with Brad Talbert and 9 others.
August 28 at 11:24 PM ¬∑

Thankful tonight for all who worked together to make our first football game a success. Covid makes life so crazy and all of us at school are trying our best to make this year a success. There are so many moving parts- new fences, new rules to meet 40 percent standards, altered concession stands and entries, social distancing, wearing masks, it is all just nuts, but we did it. What I noticed the most was that every one was just glad to be there. The parent night was fantastic, all of them were so great. The cheerleaders and the band did an excellent job and the Hornets got the win. So thankful for kindness from the fans, a nice breeze, hard working- amiable coworkers, and no injuries. Attitude of gratitude for this journey called life.

post_text: Attention Temple College Early Admissions Dual Credit students: Temple College has chosen to move all of their course online this semester. I have emailed every TC Dual Credit student a letter that highlights important days in the month of August. Please read the letter and if you have any questions, contact Mrs Cearley at the number listed in the letter. We will be passing out chromebooks for juniors and seniors attending Temple College on Wednesday, August 12 from 8:30 to 2:30 in the student center. There will be a table set up in the student center with more forms and information and Mrs. Cearley will be there in case you have specific questions.

post_text: Today, I had the privilege of being able to attend a scholarship awards banquet sponsored by the Altrusa Club of Temple. Congratulations to Nora Beebe and Brady Shelton for being recognized as one of the ten scholarship recipients awarded by the Altrusa Club. Each of these students received a 2000.00 scholarship which will help them greatly as they leave for college in August. Nora Beebe will be attending the University of North Texas and Brady Shelton will be attending Tarleton State University. Congratulations to these outstanding graduates from the class of 2020. Thank you to the Altrusa Club of Temple for the investment in our youth.

post_text: The Administration and School Board of Holland ISD have made the tough decision to cancel the in-person graduation ceremony that was scheduled for July 10, 2020. The health and safety of our graduates, their families, and our staff cannot be maintained at this time, due to the rising number of COVID-19 cases in our county and state. Holland High School worked hard to make May 22, 2020 a memorable day for our graduates; regrettably we will not be able to add the additional piece to their experience. Thank you for your patience during these very difficult times, please stay distanced and safe.

post_text:
The 2020-2021 school calendar has been revised. The new school calendar was created to add extra days to support additional learning opportunities and provide extra minutes in the calendar. The school day will be increased by 10 minutes daily and six additional days have been added to the students school year. Bad Weather days have been added at the end of May and will only be used if needed, due to school closure. School will have to continue until the appropriate number of minutes (75,600) have been completed, even if that means finishing in June due to extended school closures.
http://hollandisd.org/upload/page/0019/docs/Calendars/20-21_Calendar_Revised_6-10-2020.pdf

Holland Hornets,
Yesterday, the announcement from the Governor that school is canceled for the remainder of the 2019-2020 school year was a big disappointment for all of us. We understand it is for the safety of our community, yet are saddened by this announcement. We are so proud of our student body and the SENIOR CLASS of 2020. This SENIOR CLASS has been an AWESOME group to lead our school district. The administrative staff and the school board are working together to develop a graduation plan for our SENIORS to honor them and celebrate these exceptional young people.
We Love You Class of 2020!!!
#HornetProud2020

Holland Elementary Plant Sale

Since school has been suspended due to the Coronavirus concern, the Holland Elementary Plant Sale will not occur as previously scheduled. Instead, people can come and pick out plants whenever they would like and leave a check made out to Holland ISD in the box on the table of the big hoop house. All proceeds go to the Holland Community Food Bank and each plant only costs $0.50. Plants are available in both greenhouses so please use the trays located in the big hoop house and help yourself.

post_text: Eighteen juniors and seniors from Holland High School toured the campus of TSTC Waco. These students were able to tour the avionics technology department, the diesel equipment technology department, and the cyber security department. It was very informative. All seniors were offered the opportunity to apply for entry to TSTC, those that chose to apply while on campus were entered into a scholarship give away especially designed for those that take the educational tour. TSTC is an excellent opportunity for our students. Their tuition is affordable and their job placement is outstanding. Thank you Mrs. Christine Festa for all of your hard work in organizing this event and Mr. Raymond Matthew McCray for driving. Great day!
